Exploratory Analysis for TED Talks

By Sarah Alabdulhadi

TED is a global community, welcoming people from every discipline and culture who seek a deeper understanding of the world. TED is a nonprofit devoted to spreading ideas, usually in the form of short, powerful talks (18 minutes or less). TED began in 1984 as a conference where Technology, Entertainment and Design converged, and today covers almost all topics - from science to business to global issues - in more than 100 languages. Meanwhile, independently run TEDx events help share ideas in communities around the world. In this project, I will discover more about the world of TED, number of speakers, views, comments, languages, duration of the talk and date of the talk.

The data is shared under the Creative Commons License (just like the TED Talks) and hosted on Kaggle. You can download it here: https://www.kaggle.com/rounakbanik/ted-talks

The dataset contains metadata about all talks hosted on the TED.com website until 21 Sep 2017. The dataset contains 17 variables and 2550 observations.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset contains 2550 TED talks with 17 features.

Features:

name: The official name of the TED Talk. Includes the title and the speaker.

title: The title of the talk

description: A blurb of what the talk is about.

main_speaker: The first named speaker of the talk.

speaker_occupation: The occupation of the main speaker.

num_speaker: The number of speakers in the talk.

duration: The duration of the talk in seconds.

event: The TED/TEDx event where the talk took place.

film_date: The Unix timestamp of the filming.

published_date: The Unix timestamp for the publication of the talk on TED.com

comments: The number of first level comments made on the talk.

tags: The themes associated with the talk.

languages: The number of languages in which the talk is available.

ratings: A stringified dictionary of the various ratings given to the talk (inspiring, fascinating, jaw dropping, etc.)

related_talks: A list of dictionaries of recommended talks to watch next.

url: The URL of the talk.

views: The number of views on the talk.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features of the dataset are Views and comments. In this analysis I want to discover what makes a talk popular and how do peopple engage with TED talks.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

The number of languages each talk has will help investigate how people engage with different talks.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created a variable named duration.min to convert the duration of the talk from seconds to minutes. Moreover, I have classified the talks by month of filming date, So I can see when most of TED talks where filmed.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust,

or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

The film date was given as Unix timestamp; therefore, I had to convert it to a date in the format YYYY-mm-dd.

Reflection

The TED talks dataset has information about 2550 talks and 17 variables. Initially, I tried to get a sense of what factors might affect the popularity of a talk.I chose to focus on number of speakers, views, comments, languages, duration of the talk and date of the talk to investigate which features play the most significant role in the popularity of a talk.

First of all, most popular talks have a high number of views which definitely correct. Number of comments in each talk also indicates that this talk is popular. Moreover, popular talks are traslate to too many languages, so it reaches more audience. secondly, I found that most of the talks were held in Februray, and least were held in Janurary and Augest.

However, I found that there is no correlation between the duration of a talk and its popularity.

One last idea for future exploration would have been to analyze the ratings of a talk and explore more about audience's opinion about each talk, and if there is a positive or negative correlation between the ratings and our main features.
